From: Bedrock <bedrock@example.com>
Subject: [PATCH 4/4] random: source /dev/urandom & getrandom() from RDRAND

For deterministic fuzzing under bedrock, userspace randomness must be
controllable byte-for-byte by the hypervisor. /dev/urandom, /dev/random
and the getrandom() syscall all funnel through get_random_bytes_user(),
which normally fills the user buffer from the in-kernel ChaCha CRNG. The
CRNG is seeded deterministically (bedrock traps RDRAND/RDSEED), but its
output is laundered through ChaCha, so a fuzzer mutation of a recorded
RDRAND value cannot move a specific /dev/urandom byte.

Fill the user buffer directly from the RDRAND instruction instead.
Bedrock unconditionally traps RDRAND and serves it from the fuzzer's
input stream, so the exact bytes returned to userspace are now
fuzzer-controlled and replay deterministically. rdrand_long() is used
rather than arch_get_random_longs() so the path does not depend on the
guest having detected X86_FEATURE_RDRAND.

Signed-off-by: Bedrock <bedrock@example.com>
---
 drivers/char/random.c | 39 +++++++++++++++++----------------------
 1 file changed, 17 insertions(+), 22 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/char/random.c b/drivers/char/random.c
index b8b24b6ed..0bc9495a9 100644
--- a/drivers/char/random.c
+++ b/drivers/char/random.c
@@ -441,34 +441,31 @@ EXPORT_SYMBOL(get_random_bytes);
 
 static ssize_t get_random_bytes_user(struct iov_iter *iter)
 {
-	struct chacha_state chacha_state;
-	u8 block[CHACHA_BLOCK_SIZE];
+	unsigned long block[CHACHA_BLOCK_SIZE / sizeof(unsigned long)];
 	size_t ret = 0, copied;
+	unsigned int i;
 
 	if (unlikely(!iov_iter_count(iter)))
 		return 0;
 
 	/*
-	 * Immediately overwrite the ChaCha key at index 4 with random
-	 * bytes, in case userspace causes copy_to_iter() below to sleep
-	 * forever, so that we still retain forward secrecy in that case.
-	 */
-	crng_make_state(&chacha_state, (u8 *)&chacha_state.x[4],
-			CHACHA_KEY_SIZE);
-	/*
-	 * However, if we're doing a read of len <= 32, we don't need to
-	 * use chacha_state after, so we can simply return those bytes to
-	 * the user directly.
+	 * Bedrock determinism: serve all userspace randomness straight from
+	 * the RDRAND instruction instead of the in-kernel ChaCha CRNG.
+	 * /dev/urandom, /dev/random and the getrandom() syscall all funnel
+	 * through this function, and bedrock unconditionally traps RDRAND and
+	 * feeds it from the fuzzer's input stream -- so the exact bytes handed
+	 * to userspace become fuzzer-controlled and replay deterministically,
+	 * which a CRNG (whose output is laundered through ChaCha) can't offer.
+	 *
+	 * rdrand_long() issues RDRAND directly, without the X86_FEATURE_RDRAND
+	 * gate that arch_get_random_longs() applies, so this path does not
+	 * depend on the guest having detected the feature. Under bedrock RDRAND
+	 * always succeeds on the first try; the retry spin is purely defensive.
 	 */
-	if (iov_iter_count(iter) <= CHACHA_KEY_SIZE) {
-		ret = copy_to_iter(&chacha_state.x[4], CHACHA_KEY_SIZE, iter);
-		goto out_zero_chacha;
-	}
-
 	for (;;) {
-		chacha20_block(&chacha_state, block);
-		if (unlikely(chacha_state.x[12] == 0))
-			++chacha_state.x[13];
+		for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(block); i++)
+			while (unlikely(!rdrand_long(&block[i])))
+				cpu_relax();
 
 		copied = copy_to_iter(block, sizeof(block), iter);
 		ret += copied;
@@ -484,8 +481,6 @@ static ssize_t get_random_bytes_user(struct iov_iter *iter)
 	}
 
 	memzero_explicit(block, sizeof(block));
-out_zero_chacha:
-	chacha_zeroize_state(&chacha_state);
 	return ret ? ret : -EFAULT;
 }
 
